When building Ethereum applications on the_graph, you can leverage the power of React hooks and TanStack Query with Wagmi. This library provides a connector system that simplifies data fetching and caching. To use it, create a connector instance and pass it to the `useQuery` hook from TanStack Query. For example, you can fetch user data from the graph API like this:
```typescript
import { useQuery, useMutation } from '@tanstack/query-react-query';
import { useAccount, useContractRead } from '@wagmi/core';

const { data, isLoading, error } = useQuery(
  ['user'],
  async () => {
    const account = useAccount();
    const userData = await useContractRead(
      account.connect().address,
      'userData'
    );
    return userData;
  },
  { refetchOnWindowFocus: false, staleTime: 1000 * 60 * 5 }
);
```
This code snippet fetches user data from the graph API when the component mounts and updates it every 5 minutes. You can customize the fetcher function to suit your specific use case.

When building on the_graph, you can now replace Ethers with Viem, a TypeScript-first, lightweight, and low-level library. Viem provides better performance and a more concise API. To migrate, you'll need to update your queries to use Viem's `createClient` function, which accepts the same options as `the_graph's` `graphqlClient`.

const viemClient = createClient({ url: 'https://api.thegraph.com/subgraphs/name/your-subgraph' });
const query = gql` query { ... } `;
viejClient.query({ query });

Viem's query builder is designed for complex queries, so you may need to refactor your existing queries to take advantage of its features.

