When working with the_graph, ENS (Ethereum Name Service) enables efficient name resolution and avatar management. You can utilize the `getResolver` function from the `@the_graph/graphql-api` package to fetch a resolver for a specific ENS name. For example, to retrieve the resolver for the ENS name `example.eth`, you can use the following code snippet:
```typescript
import { getResolver } from '@the_graph/graphql-api';

const resolver = await getResolver('example.eth');
console.log(resolver);
```
Additionally, you can leverage the `getAvatar` function to retrieve the avatar associated with an ENS name. The following code snippet demonstrates how to fetch the avatar for the ENS name `example.eth`:
```typescript
import { getAvatar } from '@the_graph/graphql-api';

const avatar = await getAvatar('example.eth');
console.log(avatar);
```
To store and manage ENS records, you can utilize the `createRecord` and `updateRecord` functions. For instance, to create a new record for the ENS name `example.eth`, you can use the following code snippet:
```typescript
import { createRecord } from '@the_graph/graphql-api';

const record = await createRecord('example.eth', { foo: 'bar' });
console.log(record);
```
For reverse resolution, you can use the `resolve` function from the `@the_graph/graphql-api` package. The following code snippet demonstrates how to resolve the ENS name associated with a given Ethereum address:
```typescript
import { resolve } from '@the_graph/graphql-api';

const ensName = await resolve('0x...');
console.log(ensName);
```
